# pins.env — SI-5 [X3] colima/lima version pins (plan §6/SI-5).
#
# THE VERIFIED-GOOD NETWORKING BASELINE. On exactly this stack the pod→host
# loopback gate was proven empirically (2026-07-03, read-only, recorded in
# docs/research/findings/x3-virtualization-colima-k3s.md §5): a pod inside
# k3s-in-Colima reached a host service bound strictly to 127.0.0.1 via
# host.lima.internal → 192.168.5.2, by IP AND by DNS name — no 0.0.0.0
# rebind required. Upstream history (colima#698, colima#653) shows older
# Lima networking did NOT behave this way, so the working state is treated
# as an implementation detail: PINNED, and re-proven by
# probe-pod-host-loopback.sh before any upgrade is accepted
# (docs/runbooks/colima.md — the probe is a MANDATORY upgrade gate).
#
# Sourced by the probe script; KEY="value" lines only, shell-parseable.
# Update these values ONLY as the final step of the runbook's upgrade
# procedure, in the same change that records a green probe run.

AIB_COLIMA_PIN="0.10.1"
AIB_LIMA_PIN="2.1.1"

# Adjunct-cluster context (informational for the pod leg; k3s is NEVER a
# dependency of session launch or LM Studio access [X3]):
AIB_K3S_BASELINE="v1.33.4+k3s1"
AIB_MACOS_BASELINE="26.6"

# Read-only re-verification of the installed toolchain against these pins
# (`colima version` / `limactl --version` / `sw_vers -productVersion` — no
# VM operation of any kind):
#   2026-07-03  findings baseline recorded (x3 doc §1 ground truth)
#   2026-07-04  SI-5 M4 slice: colima 0.10.1 (aarch64, docker runtime),
#               limactl 2.1.1, macOS 26.6 — MATCHES the pins; no drift.
